WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Good morning.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Today is Saturday, March 9, 2013.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:19.000
My name is Dr. Asan Kwanbi-Jeffries of Ohio State University in Southern Illinois,

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:23.000
a history program at the University of North Carolina and Chapel Hill,

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:30.000
I'm with the Oliver Burr at Nileego in Albany, Georgia, on the campus of Albany State University.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.000
They conduct an interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:41.000
which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture and the Library.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:47.000
We are here with Dr. Clifford, David, Cliff Browner, Jr.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:49.000
Thank you so much.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:58.000
I want to begin this conversation on discussion here with some background information.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Mr. Browner, could you tell us when and where you were born?

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:09.000
Born to me, seven, seven, seven, seven, six, and Georgia, that's in Terracalty.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:13.000
And your parents, what were their names?

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:15.000
My father's name was Clifford.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.000
My mother's name was Johnny Lou.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:19.000
And where were they born?

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:23.000
My father was born in Webster County and my mother was born in Terracalty.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:27.000
Webster's a few miles north of Terracalty.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Do you know how they met?

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.000
I remember her telling me a story.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:40.000
She was at school one day and it was right after her mother had passed

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
and her grandmother sent her to the woodpile to get wood.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:52.000
And she prayed to the Lord to send her somebody that would love her and care for her.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
And she said she went to school the next day my father set behind her.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.000
She said never said anything to her before.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:05.000
But this particular day after she prayed, he touched on the shoulder and asked if she thought her grandmother

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
would mind if he came to see her.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:10.000
And that's how they started.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:12.000
You said they met in school?

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.000
How long were they able to go to school?

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.000
How much schooling did they get?

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:24.000
I believe my father told me he completed 3 grade and my mother was about 8 grade.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:25.000
I believe it's correct.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:29.000
Your father, he was a sharecropper.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
No, or did he work the land?

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:33.000
He started out sharecropping.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:39.000
And I think by the time I was failure those he came off of the farm and took a job in Albionist.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.000
He swiped for a lasso, complained.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:44.000
And that's what he retired from.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.000
So you worked there for a number of years?

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:47.000
Yes.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:52.000
And how far was Albionist from your home?

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.000
A roughly 20 miles.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:05.000
Did you find as a child growing up that you would often go to Albionist or did you tend to stay more around your home in Saftler and Terrell?

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.000
Well there were occasions when weekends in particular that he would bring us to the zoo in Albion.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.000
And that was a fun day.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:17.000
And this of course was segregated, right?

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:18.000
Yeah, it was still segregated.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:23.000
So what was your experience like coming to Albionist at that time?

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:34.000
Well actually, I didn't actually run into much segregation in the sense of the word because my father kept us shielded from that to a point.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:40.000
Now we knew it existed but nobody really bothered us as a family.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:47.000
So some of the things that you would hear about the sound I really didn't experience because of that protection that he put in force.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
And by protection, how did he do that?

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:54.000
What do you mean that nobody bothered you because of this protection?

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:58.000
Well one thing, if we went in place, I'm going to have to go.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:01.000
So, I think we worked during the summer.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.000
We could only work if she worked in the same place we worked.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
So you made sure that we were always looked after.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
And I never had the opportunity to work for fights in the year.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.000
I couldn't crash or couldn't head just to things like that.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:17.000
He didn't allow us to do that because he wasn't there to look after it.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:22.000
So he made sure we stayed home and let my mother could actually be there.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:28.000
So I never really had any really confrontations per se as a child in that respect.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:31.000
What was the community like that you grew up in?

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
The black community.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:38.000
If you sheltered from sort of being exposed to white working in that,

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.000
what was the community like that you were exposed to that you were growing up in?

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:46.000
Well we basically lived in all black communities of course.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
There were dirt streets and the houses that didn't have paint.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:52.000
And most of them were three room houses.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:57.000
And of course there were varied numbers of family members living in our case.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.000
There were extended family members there.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:02.000
So the community itself was basically black.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:07.000
And we didn't have any real control of what went on.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:14.000
So if you learn how to live within that city,

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.000
you avoid it trouble.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:22.000
But for lack of a better way of putting it stand in your place.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
So there were differences.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:30.000
If we went outside that we knew there were ways we were supposed to care ourselves.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:34.000
In front of whites we were just certain of certain, yes ma'am, no ma'am,

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
what it was spoken to.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
And how did you pick up on those?

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
Is this something that your mother said that you have to do?

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:50.000
How did you learn those particular ways to interact with white folks?

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.000
Well some of us started home and some of you picked up from interactions.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:59.000
You saw other people do certain things and you just followed suit.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:02.000
And you weren't the only child.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Your parents had how many children total?

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:08.000
I have four of us.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:13.000
Two boys, two girls, two sisters, two sisters older and my brothers,

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:15.000
I was in their child.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.000
But my mother raised and father raised over the children.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:21.000
I had a cousin at Lywoodville saying,

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:24.000
her mother at some point and my mother raised her baby sister and brother

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:27.000
from her mother's marriage.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:29.000
So you had a four household as you were saying.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:32.000
You grew up with a house full of people.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:37.000
And I thought there was always somebody there that really wasn't an out immediate family.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.000
All through my teenage life growing up.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:46.000
So my family always took care of my cousin and some other people.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:51.000
And there were instances where even brother and mother were living with us at some point.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:55.000
Now what elementary school did you go to?

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.000
The elementary school that I attended was done by elementary school.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:04.000
And it's the building that side is the other end of the building that's been torn down.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
And what was done by life?

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.000
Done by life.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
White, maybe I should say, it had been white.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:19.000
But, you know, well it had faded in so it was a dull looking white building.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:27.000
There weren't any indoor facilities with heated by a pot-bending stove in the middle of the room.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:31.000
And you know, you went to one class, you pre-med stayed there,

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:34.000
you teach and talk to everything from that classroom.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:39.000
We asked children to go out on the head road, we called it,

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:43.000
to cut wood to start to fire in the stoves.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:48.000
And there were underneath the, what we were called a crawl space now.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:51.000
The coal was still underneath the building.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.000
So we were going under the building, under the building.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:59.000
And we were going to go out with buckets and a shovel to get coal green and to keep the fire going and the stove doing the one-a-tang.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.000
So this is what you and your classmates would do, yes.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:09.000
And of course, when you, the facilities were outside, they had two facilities, one for the boys, one for the girls, I say.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:13.000
There were no indoor facilities, no running water.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:19.000
And did your siblings also go to Dunbar as well?

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
They, they, they may not have because they were older.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.000
You know, because I don't know if that's been a long while back.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:31.000
So some things I don't remember specifically, but they may not have gone there as much as I did because I was young and the young's one of them.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.000
Now did you stay in Dunbar all the way up until high school?

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:42.000
No, actually the first Dunbar, they built a new school in, I think, 1955.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:49.000
And after that, I, I left there and went to Carver, which is the Dundhsendjurge, which is called High School, the Dundhsendjurge.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:54.000
And I think I went to eighth grade from Dunbar.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:59.000
And how far was Carver? I mean, because that was a little bit further away from where you lived.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:04.000
Seven miles. And how did you get to school bus?

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
Yeah, we were bus from Sassar. Bus would come to Dunbar, pick it up.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:16.000
They would do actually pick the ones up in the country, bring them to Dunbar, then they would lead there and go to Carver.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:25.000
And thinking about the kind of education that you would see, the quality of education, reflecting back on it.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.000
I mean, what did you, how would you say it was?

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:34.000
You feel that you got a good foundation, that it was just as good as anything you could have gotten.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.000
What would you say?

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
Well, first of all, I believe that if you apply, you said, wherever you are, you would get a good education.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:45.000
But also, you know, we weren't exposed to a lot of stuff.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:52.000
So it wasn't in theory in that sense that we just didn't get exposed to things that were in other places.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.000
The education, teach the work and serve it in the value.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
And what they were able to teach you, they wanted you to learn that.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
But, you know, I still say that in the end of this one in theory education.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:10.000
Did your parents talk much about school to you growing up?

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:16.000
They are concerned with that we would get an education because they knew that we were the key to a better life.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
So, you know, we never had to stay out of school to work.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
That was one of the advantages of my father not being on the phone.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:27.000
The insistent that we go to school.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:33.000
So, when the other children had to stay out because they were crossing the field, we didn't have to.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:38.000
So, that was the advantage I saw of him not being on the phone.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:42.000
Now, your mother, what does she do for the...

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.000
Did she work outside of the home?

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:48.000
She did, they labor her domestic laborer.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:53.000
She worked, she cooked, took care of the white's babies and clean house.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:59.000
And eventually she worked at the white elementary school that was in SAS as a cook.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:05.000
And eventually she went to, from there to Donbar when they were able to be on the new school.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:11.000
When they had lunchroom, she worked in that lunchroom and then eventually she took a tat and then lunchroom and call her.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:18.000
Now, she was working at SAS, when did she begin working at the white school, at the white school?

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:27.000
She worked in the white school during the time I was in school so I don't know the year but it was like it would have been in the fielder.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:38.000
So now, when the sort of protests begin, so the civil rights protests begin in Albany in early 1960s, 1961.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:43.000
In terror a little bit later, in really 1963.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:49.000
You're still young, you're not in high school yet, are you?

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
Yes, you are in high school.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:59.000
So when things begin in Albany first, were you aware of them?

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
How did you become aware of them?

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
Do you remember hearing about them at all?

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
The first time you began hearing about things going on?

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.000
My father and my father were involved, my system was involved.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:13.000
Older, one older, one older, one older sister was involved.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:16.000
So that's how I knew about the movement.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:25.000
I didn't initially start out attending mass meetings but that came later as they moved the mass media to the church where we remember.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.000
And that church was my own out of the church in SAS.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
Now, about my own out of it, that was your family's church?

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:33.000
Yes.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:37.000
Was it a big church, big membership, small church?

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:43.000
For that time, it was a medium, so I think a membership church for that time.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:50.000
There were four other churches, a five other churches in SAS and Facility.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:54.000
And I think we met on full Sundays.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:58.000
Only on the full Sundays at Mount Olive, once a month.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:01.000
Now, were your parents active in the church?

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
And your church groups, church memberships?

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
My dad, I know worked in finance.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
I mean, I can remember as a young and child in money.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:09.000
So I know he worked in finance.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:14.000
I don't know if he lived with chairman, mother decimble, but I know he was decimble there and I know he worked in finance.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.000
And he can make past a trustee working in finance.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:19.000
They didn't call it that bank, right?

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:20.000
Yeah.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:23.000
He was responsible for getting the money to the bank and that kind of thing.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:25.000
And how about your mother?

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:32.000
My mother, I don't remember her holding an office in church doing that time.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:37.000
Because they held membership in two different churches actually.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
But she attended Monalda frequently.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:48.000
People really thought she was a member of Monalda, but she actually was a member of Santa's gift baptism church, which is about two or three miles from where we lived.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:54.000
But she was always at Monalda, so nobody ever questioned whether she was a member of that.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:59.000
Now, your church memories are they Monalda's church memories?

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
Do you remember attending Monalda's?

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:02.000
Yes, I did.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:07.000
You know, like, southern schools, east of plays, singing in a church choir.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:11.000
You know, in the choir board, there's more than singing in the choir.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:18.000
Now, how important was that church life to you and your family?

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:23.000
Well, it was a thing that we believed in doing.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:26.000
We believed that God, we needed God in our lives.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:29.000
And we attended church very often.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:37.000
It wasn't like we went once, we went to every two or three months, and we went every month to that church.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:41.000
And occasionally, I would go with my mother to Santa's gift.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:43.000
So church life was important to us.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:47.000
That church was my father a little bit of church.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:55.000
And, you know, one of the requests he made before he died was that for me not to let church die.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:58.000
So that's how important it was to him.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:17.000
So, do you recall at all any of the conversation that went into deciding that the church should open its doors to a mass meeting, to the movement when it begins organizing in the teller county?

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:30.000
Well, I wasn't privy to a conversation of that soul, but I know that they had been meeting that Zion grow, I believe, a Zion heal, which was in Stereocardi but out from Carlson.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:36.000
And I was told from conversation that the people in that area was not attending the meeting.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:43.000
So, they moved into the sassages of the Monata because that's what the book of the people were coming from that were going to the Zion.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:54.000
And the fact that pastors aren't here that time lived in sassages, so they brought into Monata where it was closer to the majority of the people who were attending.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.000
So, that's, you know, pretty much the reason that they moved in.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:01.000
And you remember some of the mass meetings at Monata?

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:02.000
At Monata, yes.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:03.000
What were they like? What were they like?

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:15.000
They were excited meetings. I mean, you know, people, the first time I really saw blacks and whites intermingling in a close vicinity that way was at those meetings.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:25.000
And there was spirit feeling all the times, there were scriptures read, conversations about what went on in other areas of Thereocardi or Lee County,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:29.000
and Lee County, on Dirty, were brought back on those meeting nights.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:40.000
And you hear who had been beaten up or who had been arrested or, you know, who had a confrontation with the Sheriff Department or police or whatever.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
Those kind of things came back.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:48.000
And what kind of results was they were getting in their mess and they are voter registration drives.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:52.000
So, they were person stories told along with the singing.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:58.000
And so, now you were younger. I mean, you were only about 15, 16.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:02.000
So, you could have two young and registered a vote.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
Right.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:08.000
So, what were some of the things that you were thinking about doing?

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:18.000
And at the time, in addition to attending the mass meeting, were you doing any other activities or what sort of the mass meeting really kind of the focus of your activity?

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:26.000
Well, the mass meeting really wasn't focused in a lot of ways, but at school, Clovis Jones and I wrote a letter to the superintendent.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:34.000
And I can't remember his name at this time, but we wrote a letter to him asking for new books because the one we were getting were hamming down from the white school.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:40.000
And of course, Paige were missing in there and during the notes written in them, you know, those kind of things.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:43.000
And they were getting the new books and then we were getting the old books.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
And this is why you went high school.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:52.000
So, Clovis, it started out about five of us sat down to write the letter when the time to send the letter on the Clovis and I sat there.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:55.000
And of course, we got in trouble with the press from school.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:18:00.000
Now, did you let your parents know beforehand that you were writing this letter?

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:03.000
No, I never mentioned the level of being written.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.000
